The key test is: pass a function as a through-stream. In the original, the `if(true)` branch handles it. In the mutated code, after the `if(true)` branch, the `else if(true)` would also try to execute... but wait, `else if` only runs if the `if` was false. Since `if(true)` is always true, the `else if` never runs.

So the mutation `else if (true)` vs `else if (s && typeof s === 'object')` - since both are in an `else if` after `if(true)`, neither ever executes! The mutation has no effect... unless the `if(true)` was originally something else.

